sections.english:
Form, monks, is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self. What is non-self should be seen as it actually is with perfect wisdom thus: 'This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.' Feeling is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self. What is non-self should be seen as it actually is with perfect wisdom thus: 'This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.' Perception is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self. What is non-self should be seen as it actually is with perfect wisdom thus: 'This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.' Formations are impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self. What is non-self should be seen as it actually is with perfect wisdom thus: 'This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.' Consciousness is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering; what is suffering is non-self. What is non-self should be seen as it actually is with perfect wisdom thus: 'This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.'

Seeing thus, monks, a well-instructed noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form, with feeling, with perception, with formations, and with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate; through dispassion, he is liberated. When liberated, there arises the knowledge: 'I am liberated.' He understands: 'Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more for this state of being.' As far as there are abodes of beings, monks, as far as the peak of existence, these are the foremost, these are the most excellent in the world, namely, the Arahants.

The Blessed One said this. Having said this, the Fortunate One, the Teacher, further said this:

Truly happy are the Arahants, craving is not found in them;
The 'I am' conceit is utterly cut off, the net of delusion is torn apart.

They have attained freedom from agitation, their minds are untroubled;
They are unattached in the world, they have become Brahma-like, taint-free.

Having fully understood the five aggregates, they abide within the seven true Dhamma principles;
They are praiseworthy good people, true children of the Buddha.

Endowed with the seven treasures, trained in the three trainings;
These great heroes wander forth, having abandoned fear and terror.

Endowed with ten qualities, these great ones are composed;
Indeed, these are the most excellent in the world; craving is not found in them.

The knowledge of one beyond training has arisen for them; this is their final body;
In this essence of the holy life, they are independent of others.

They do not tremble amidst distinctions, utterly freed from renewed existence;
Having attained the state of the tamed, they are victorious in the world.

Upward, across, downward, delight is not found in them;
They roar the lion's roar, these awakened ones, unsurpassed in the world.
